        <article class='well'>
          <h1>Redesign Day</h1>
          <p>One small step for the web, one giant leap for responsive web design. I'm being dramatic, but yesterday was a big day for #RWD and the web in general. It was redesign launch day, with <a href="http://elementcreative.com">Element</a> and <a href="http://paravelinc.com">Paravel</a> both showing off their latest versions of their sites. As cool as they are, two web shops releasing responsive redesigns isn't that big of a deal.</p>
          
          <p><a href="http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/default.aspx">Microsoft</a> and <a href="http://disney.com">Disney</a> kind of are, though. Microsoft released only a home page redesign, but it's a great step in the right direction. Disney went further than the home page but still has plenty of content linked that isn't responsiveâ€¦yet. The reason that I see this as important is that they are introducing it to their markets and leading them by doing it. This will be huge for enterprise and entertainment sites.</p>
          
          <p>Wordpress introduced responsive to publishers with their free 2011 theme. This enabled publishers to begin producing content that could then be consumed more easily across a wide range of devices. The Boston Globe lead the charge into news/media delivery and now we will see the demand surge in business and entertainment. With a much wider array of content, there will be fantastic solutions that come out of the teams behind these projects. It is going to be an exciting couple of years.</p>
        </article>
